<subSubSection id="CCCB0B769ED37CD7B3179791A22F8FF8" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="594A8907BD505A5F60FB301055F5BFB5" pageId="8" pageNumber="85">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FC62C19F53FC9D34BBEA3DBA7F4F9E97" pageId="8" pageNumber="85">Very slender body, fore coxae are armed with a long and flattened spine, cerci long and decussate.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B24B2C11221CCDCAC9759B27E438755A" pageId="8" pageNumber="85" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="61DA3FB6C7E132D93CDCEB134B40C3B4" pageId="8" pageNumber="85">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4271D0C1F5562C30E93C3C7E004B5591" pageId="8" pageNumber="85">From Latin: spiniger = thorny, after the long and stout spine on the fore coxae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
